### Proposed relations to other language families

For centuries, the [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages) stood as stark linguistic isolates, enigmatic and seemingly unconnected to any other known family. Before 2008, few linguists, if any, were willing to endorse connections between [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) and other major linguistic groups, despite various distant connections being proposed, often with a rather unconvincing enthusiasm, to most of the [ergative languages](/Ergative_language) of Eurasia. Such grand theories are, of course, a perennial favorite among those who seek to impose order on the chaotic sprawl of human communication, often with little to show for it but a new set of academic squabbles.

#### Dene–Yeniseian

Then, in 2008, [Edward Vajda](/Edward_Vajda) of [Western Washington University](/Western_Washington_University) presented a meticulously crafted body of evidence for a [genealogical relation](/Genetic_relationship_(linguistics)) between the [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages) of [Siberia](/Siberia) and the [Na–Dene languages](/Na%E2%80%93Den%C3%A9_languages) of North America. This was, by all accounts, a rather significant moment, a potential bridge across the Bering Strait built not of ice, but of shared linguistic heritage. At the time of its publication in 2010, Vajda's proposals received a notably favorable, if occasionally cautious, reception from several specialists in both Na-Dene and [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages). This cadre of respected linguists included luminaries such as [Michael Krauss](/Michael_E._Krauss), Jeff Leer, [James Kari](/James_Kari), and Heinrich Werner, alongside a host of other esteemed scholars like [Bernard Comrie](/Bernard_Comrie), [Johanna Nichols](/Johanna_Nichols), [Victor Golla](/Victor_Golla), [Michael Fortescue](/Michael_Fortescue), [Eric Hamp](/Eric_P._Hamp), and Bill Poser (as documented in Kari and Potter 2010:12).

However, as with all ambitious academic endeavors, dissenting voices soon emerged. A significant exception to this general acceptance was the critical review of the collected papers by [Lyle Campbell](/Lyle_Campbell), published in late 2011. Campbell's critique, and Vajda's subsequent response, clearly indicated that the proposal was far from being universally "settled" at that time. Campbell famously concluded: "In summary, the proposed Dene-Yeniseian connection cannot be embraced at present. The hypothesis is indeed stimulating, advanced by a serious scholar trying to use appropriate procedures. Unfortunately, neither the lexical evidence (with putative sound correspondences) nor the morphological evidence adduced is sufficient to support a distant genetic relationship between Na-Dene and Yeniseian" (pg. 450). Vajda, in his measured response, acknowledged the ongoing challenges: "It remains incumbent upon the proponents of the DY hypothesis to provide solutions to at least some of the unresolved problems identified in Campbell's review or in DYC itself. My opinion is that every one of them requires a convincing solution before the relationship between Yeniseian and Na-Dene can be considered settled" (pg. 452). Two other reviews and notices concerning the volume also appeared in 2011, penned by [Keren Rice](/Keren_Rice) and [Jared Diamond](/Jared_Diamond), further underscoring the dynamic and evolving nature of this linguistic debate. It seems even the most groundbreaking theories are not immune to the relentless scrutiny of the academic world.

#### Karasuk

The [Karasuk hypothesis](/Karasuk_languages), a rather intriguing proposition, suggests a deep linguistic link between [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) and the utterly unique [Burushaski language](/Burushaski_language), spoken in the remote valleys of northern Pakistan. This connection has been championed by several scholars over the years, most notably by A.P. Dulson and V.N. Toporov, who, one presumes, found joy in tracing such unlikely linguistic threads. In 2001, [George van Driem](/George_van_Driem) further elaborated on this, postulating that the [Burusho people](/Burusho_people) were part of a significant migration wave out of Central Asia, a movement that ultimately culminated in the Indo-European conquest of the [Indus Valley](/Indus_Valley_Civilization). This paints a picture of ancient population movements and linguistic intermingling, where the [Yeniseians](/Yeniseian_peoples) might be connected to groups far beyond their immediate Siberian confines. More recently, Alexei Kassian has ventured to suggest an even broader connection, proposing lexical correspondences between [Hattic](/Hattic_language), [Hurro-Urartian](/Hurro-Urartian_languages), and the [Karasuk group](/Karasuk_languages), hinting at a vast, ancient linguistic network stretching across Eurasia.

#### Sino–Tibetan

As noted by Tailleur and Werner, some of the earliest proposals for [genetic relations](/Genetic_relationship_(linguistics)) of [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) date back to the mid-19th and early 20th centuries. Figures like [M.A. Castrén](/Matthias_Castr%C3%A9n) (1856), James Byrne (1892), and G.J. Ramstedt (1907) suggested that [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) might be a northern relative of the vast [Sino–Tibetan languages](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) family. These early, somewhat speculative, ideas were later revisited and expanded upon by scholars such as Kai Donner (1930) and Karl Bouda (1957, 1963). The concept received a renewed impetus in the 21st century when a 2008 study presented further evidence for a possible, albeit distant, relationship between [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) and [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages), citing several potential [cognates](/Cognates)—words sharing a common origin. Gao Jingyi (2014) intensified this discussion by identifying twelve shared etymologies between Sinitic (a branch of [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages)) and [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) that belonged to the most basic vocabulary. She argued, rather convincingly, that these Sino–Yeniseian etymologies were unlikely to be mere loans from one language to the other, suggesting a deeper, more ancient connection.

The ambitious "[Sino–Caucasian](/Sino-Caucasian)" hypothesis, championed by the late [Sergei Starostin](/Sergei_Starostin), posits that the [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages) form a distinct [clade](/Clade) (a group of languages sharing a common ancestor) with [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages), a grouping he somewhat poetically termed "Sino–Yeniseian." This hypothesis has, predictably, been expanded upon by others, morphing into the even more encompassing "[Dene–Caucasian](/Dene%E2%80%93Caucasian)" theory. This grander framework attempts to incorporate the [Na-Dene languages](/Na-Dene_languages) of North America, [Burushaski](/Burushaski_language), [Basque](/Basque_language), and, on occasion, even the enigmatic [Etruscan language](/Etruscan_language)—a rather impressive, if perhaps overly optimistic, attempt to connect disparate linguistic dots across continents and millennia. However, while the narrower, binary [Dene–Yeniseian family](/Den%C3%A9%E2%80%93Yeniseian_languages) has recently gained considerable traction, the broader validity of the rest of the "[Dene–Caucasian](/Dene%E2%80%93Caucasian)" family is largely viewed as doubtful or outright rejected by nearly all mainstream [historical linguists](/Historical_linguists), a clear indication that not all ambitious theories stand the test of rigorous scrutiny. An updated tree proposed by [Georgiy Starostin](/Georgiy_Starostin), continuing his father's work, now groups Na-Dene with Sino–Tibetan, while placing [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) with [Burushaski](/Burushaski_language), effectively reviving and incorporating elements of the [Karasuk hypothesis](/Karasuk_languages) into a new, complex arrangement.

[George van Driem](/George_van_Driem), ever the contrarian, maintains a skeptical stance regarding a direct genetic relationship between [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) (which he prefers to call "Trans–Himalayan") and [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages). However, he does propose an alternative, equally fascinating, scenario: he argues that [Yeniseian speakers](/Yeniseian_peoples) once populated the vast expanse of the [North China Plain](/North_China_Plain). According to his theory, early [Proto-Sinitic](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) speakers, upon migrating into this region, assimilated these [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_peoples) populations. As a result of this profound linguistic and cultural contact, [Sinitic](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) acquired what he describes as "creoloid characteristics," evolving into a [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) among the ethnolinguistically diverse populations of the region. This suggests that the influence of [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) on [Sinitic](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) might be one of deep contact rather than direct genetic inheritance.

A 2023 analysis conducted by [David Bradley](/David_Bradley_(linguist)), utilizing the rigorous, standard techniques of [comparative linguistics](/Comparative_linguistics), offers further support for a distant [genetic link](/Genetic_relationship_(linguistics)) connecting the [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages), [Na–Dene](/Na%E2%80%93Den%C3%A9_languages), and [Yeniseian language families](/Yeniseian_languages). Bradley posits that any similarities [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages) might share with other language families of the East Asia area, such as [Hmong–Mien](/Hmong%E2%80%93Mien_languages), [Altaic](/Altaic_languages) (which he, like many, views as a [sprachbund](/Sprachbund) or linguistic area rather than a true genetic family), [Austroasiatic](/Austroasiatic_languages), [Kra–Dai](/Kra%E2%80%93Dai_languages), and [Austronesian](/Austronesian_languages), are primarily the result of historical contact. However, given the demonstrable lack of any recent contact between the [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages), [Na–Dene](/Na%E2%80%93Den%C3%A9_languages), and [Yeniseian language families](/Yeniseian_languages), any shared similarities among these three groups, Bradley argues, must necessarily be residual evidence of a much deeper, ancient genetic relationship. A rather elegant argument, suggesting that sometimes, the absence of recent interaction is precisely what reveals ancient ties.

#### Dene–Caucasian

The [Dene–Caucasian hypothesis](/Den%C3%A9%E2%80%93Caucasian_languages) is a truly ambitious, some might say excessively so, linguistic super-family proposal. Karl Bouda, in a series of publications spanning the 1930s to the 1950s, outlined a vast linguistic network that, in addition to [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages) and [Sino-Tibetan](/Sino-Tibetan_languages), also encompassed the diverse [Caucasian languages](/North_Caucasian_languages) and [Burushaski](/Burushaski_language). Some iterations of this expansive theory have been known under the more concise, if equally contentious, name of Sino-Caucasian. The works of scholars such as R. Bleichsteiner, O.G. Tailleur, the late [Sergei A. Starostin](/Sergei_Starostin), and [Sergei L. Nikolayev](/Sergei_L._Nikolayev) have sought, with varying degrees of success, to confirm these grand connections, painstakingly searching for shared roots across vast linguistic divides. Others who have further developed this hypothesis, often expanding it to the even more encompassing [Dene–Caucasian](/Den%C3%A9%E2%80%93Caucasian_languages) umbrella, include J.D. Bengtson, V. Blažek, [J.H. Greenberg](/Joseph_Greenberg) (in collaboration with [M. Ruhlen](/Merritt_Ruhlen)), and M. Ruhlen himself. [George Starostin](/George_Starostin) continues his father's extensive work in [Yeniseian](/Yeniseian_languages), Sino-Caucasian, and other related fields, ensuring that the debate, if nothing else, persists.

However, one must temper enthusiasm with a healthy dose of skepticism. This theory is widely regarded as extremely controversial, or at best, highly doubtful, and is outright rejected by the overwhelming majority of mainstream linguists. The sheer scope of the proposed connections, spanning continents and seemingly unrelated language families, often leads to evidence that is considered too tenuous or too generalized to meet the rigorous standards of established [comparative linguistics](/Comparative_linguistics). It appears that while some find solace in grand unifying theories, others prefer the messy, isolated realities of linguistic diversity.

