1.  ^ The figure of 156 native speakers represents the sum of [Ket](/Ket_language) and [Yugh](/Yugh_language) speakers recorded in the [2021 Russian census](/2021_Russian_census). One might note that even with the most generous accounting, this number remains astonishingly, almost tragically, small.
2.  ^ The term "[Ostyak](/Ostyak)" is a rather antiquated and imprecise concept, rooted more in [areal linguistics](/Language_geography) (geographical proximity) than in true [genetic linguistics](/Genetic_relationship_(linguistics)) (shared ancestry). Historically, it was a catch-all term that, in addition to encompassing the [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages), also included the distinct [Uralic languages](/Uralic_languages) of [Khanty](/Khanty_language) and [Selkup](/Selkup_language). Consequently, the compound term "Yenisei-Ostyak" typically refers specifically to the Ketic branch of the [Yeniseian family](/Yeniseian_languages), attempting to narrow down a historically broad and often confusing designation. Such is the enduring legacy of early, less nuanced classifications.
3.  ^ Yastin, Yarin, and Baikot are often, and perhaps pragmatically, considered to be mere dialects of [Kott](/Kott_language). In the face of complete extinction, the precise classification of such minor variations becomes, one might argue, a rather academic exercise, a subtle distinction on a tombstone.
4.  ^ The numerals '8' and '9' in some [Yeniseian languages](/Yeniseian_languages) are clearly identified as Russian loanwords. This is a rather stark and undeniable indicator of cultural and linguistic contact, demonstrating the profound influence of a dominant language on a smaller, more vulnerable one, a common pattern in the relentless march of linguistic history.

